### Friend Function

A friend function is a non-member function that has access to a class's private and protected members. It is declared inside the class with the `friend` keyword.

---

### Syntax

```cpp
class ClassName {
  friend returnType functionName(parameters);
};
```

---

### Example

```cpp
class Rectangle {
private:
  double width, height;

public:
  Rectangle(double w, double h) : width(w), height(h) {}

  friend double calculateArea(const Rectangle& rect);
};

double calculateArea(const Rectangle& rect) {
  return rect.width * rect.height;  // Access private members
}
```

---

### Friend Class

A class can be a friend of another class:

```cpp
class A {
  friend class B;  // B has access to all private members of A
private:
  int secret;
};

class B {
public:
  void reveal(A& a) {
    cout << a.secret;  // Allowed: B is friend of A
  }
};
```

---

### Friend Characteristics

| Property | Description |
|----------|-------------|
| Not inherited | Friendship is not passed to derived classes |
| Not transitive | A friend of B does not mean B is friend of A |
| Not symmetric | A is friend of B does not mean B is friend of A |
| Can be function or class | Both supported |

---

> **Key Point:** Use friend functions sparingly. They break encapsulation and should only be used when a non-member function genuinely needs access to private members (e.g., operator overloading).

codeExample:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Box {
private:
  double length;

public:
  Box(double l) : length(l) {}

  friend void printLength(const Box& b);
};

void printLength(const Box& b) {
  cout << "Length: " << b.length << endl;
}

int main() {
  Box box(10.5);
  printLength(box);
  return 0;
}
